				<h1>Lit Hub’s Most Anticipated Books of 2025, Part Two</h1>
		<h2>249 Books to Read Before the End of the Year</h2>
    <div class="inner">
		<div class="post_header_wrapper">
    				</div>
				<div class="author_info" itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
			<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">Literary&nbsp;Hub</span></a></div>
			<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
			<div class="publish_date">July 1, 2025</div>
		</div>
		<div class="social_links">
						<a href="https://twitter.com/intent/tweet?via=lithub&text=Lit+Hub%E2%80%99s+Most+Anticipated+Books+of+2025%2C+Part+Two&url=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Flit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two%2F"><span class="social_twitter"></span></a>
			<a href="https://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flithub.com%2Flit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two%2F&t=Lit+Hub%E2%80%99s+Most+Anticipated+Books+of+2025%2C+Part+Two"><span class="social_facebook"></span></a>
					</div>
    <div class="inner">
    	<!-- Begin main content -->
    	<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
    			
										<!-- Begin each blog post -->
						<div class="post_wrapper" style="padding-top:0;">
							<div class="post_inner_wrapper">
						    	<div class="post_wrapper_inner">
										<div class="inner_wrapper fullwidth">
								        
										<p>Time keeps on slippin&#8217; into the future, and the books keep right on coming, no matter what&#8217;s going on outside. Want to fly like an eagle? Already finished everything on <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">this list</a>? Check out the books the Literary Hub staff is most looking forward to reading in the back half of 2025 below, and get ready for the revolution.</p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><script id="9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23">(new Image()).src = 'https://capi.connatix.com/tr/si?token=546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff&cid=86b7c382-5e20-4129-84db-dea768f4d688';  cnx.cmd.push(function() {    cnx({      playerId: "546998bb-b9c0-4480-8c91-3e307220efff"    }).render("9b7a21a47fb44523b011db6d4f4cad23");  });</script></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h1>July</h1>
<h4><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255686" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9780374612986-1/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1.jpg" data-orig-size="652,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Geovani Martins, tr. Julia Sanches, Via Ápia" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255686" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1-196x300.jpg" alt="Geovani Martins, tr. Julia Sanches, Via Ápia" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780374612986-1.jpg 652w" sizes="(max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></h4>
<h4><strong>Geovani Martins, tr. Julia Sanches, <em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374612986" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external">Via Ápia</a></em><br />
FSG Originals, July 1</strong></h4>
<p>Not to be all “as someone who was an English minor…” but as someone who was an English minor, I love an epic. An epic set in modern day Rio is even better. <em>Via Ápia</em> follows a group of young people whose lives are upended by a police occupation of their neighborhood. Set just before the 2011 World Cup and Olympics (both of which took place in Rio) and told over the course of a year and a half, Martin’s debut novel explores themes of state violence, resistance, friendship, and life in the modern world. Also, I love Julia Sanches! She’s a wonderful translator. <em>Via Ápia</em> is sure to be great. <em>–McKayla Coyle, Publishing Coordinator</em></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255687" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9781982160074-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Michael Grunwald, We Are Eating the Earth" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255687" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy-199x300.jpg" alt="Michael Grunwald, We Are Eating the Earth" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781982160074-copy.jpg 663w" sizes="(max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Michael Grunwald, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781982160074" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>We Are Eating the Earth</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Simon &amp; Schuster, July 1</strong></h4>
<p>We all know fossil fuels are bad. And we all actually know how to function without them… The problem here is one of politics, not solutions. But did you know that we’re also facing an imminent scarcity threat in terms of land use? That’s right, at current rates, by around the middle of this century, the earth won’t have enough land to feed its ever-growing population—this is also very bad! The good news is that not only does <em><span style="font-weight: 400;">We Are Eating the Earth </span></em>point out this alarming reality, it also offers some viable solutions. <em>–Jonny Diamond, Editor in Chief</em></p>
<h4><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255688" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9781963108279-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="647,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Claire Jia, Wanting" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255688" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy-194x300.jpg" alt="Claire Jia, Wanting" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781963108279-copy.jpg 647w" sizes="(max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></h4>
<h4><strong>Claire Jia, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781963108279" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Wanting</a></em><br />
Tin House, July 1</strong></h4>
<p>I love a novel with a secret, and Claire Jia’s debut is bursting with them. <em>Wanting</em> follows Ye Lian and Luo Wenyu, high school best friends who drifted apart due to distance and minor YouTube celebrity, as they reunite in Beijing, now in their thirties and grappling with the calcification of their life choices. A gripping exploration of friendship, envy, desire, wealth, ambition, and contemporary Beijing, <em>Wanting</em> is both juicy and substantial. <em>–Jessie Gaynor, Senior Editor, <a href="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our summer reading list</a></em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255689" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9780063305823-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Maris Kreizman, I Want to Burn This Place Down: Essays" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255689" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy-199x300.jpg" alt="Maris Kreizman, I Want to Burn This Place Down: Essays" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780063305823-copy.jpg 662w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Maris Kreizman, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780063305823" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>I Want to Burn This Place Down: Essays</em></a><br />
Ecco, July 1<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>Full disclosure: Maris Kreizman is a columnist at this website and I love working with her. She is principled, willing to speak truth to power, and uses her years of experience in the publishing industry to highlight its absurdities and hypocrisies while also celebrating the work of so many of its workers. AND she has a sense of humor. (NB: these things don’t always go together). So am I thrilled that she has a full-blown essay collection coming out that will, among other things, demonstrate to readers “that it’s never too late to become radicalized.” A-fucking-men. <em>–JD, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255690" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/912po-h8aul-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="659,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Nell Stevens, The Original" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255690" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" alt="Nell Stevens, The Original" width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/912po-h8AuL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 659w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Nell Stevens, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324110699" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Original</a><br />
</em>W.W. Norton, July 1</strong></h4>
<p>I’ve been proselytizing Nell Stevens’ first book, <em>Briefly, A Delicious Life</em> since it came out a few years ago. It’s one of my all-time favorites, the kind of book that’s always in the back of my mind, that I come back to all the time. So I was beyond excited to find out there’s a new Nell Stevens book coming out this summer! And it’s a total banger! I literally couldn’t put this book down. I thought about it constantly while I was reading it. If that’s not a recommendation, I don’t know what is.</p>
<p>The novel follows a young woman, Grace, who secretly becomes an incredible art forger. Just as she begins to use her talent professionally, a man shows up claiming to be her long-lost cousin—but Grace’s face-blindness makes it impossible for her to know whether he’s really her cousin or not. It’s a novel about fakes and copies and originality and the meaning of art and it has so many delicious layers to unwrap. It’s like <em>F for Fake</em> (1973) by way of <em>Jane Eyre</em> or <em>O Caledonia</em>. It’s thoughtful and haunting and beautifully written. A perfect gothic novel to add to your summer reading list! <em>–MC, <a href="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our summer reading list</a></em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247605" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/benedict-nguyen-hot-girls-with-balls/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls-.jpeg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Benedict Nguyễn, Hot Girls With Balls" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls--199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls-.jpeg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-247605" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls--199x300.jpeg" alt="Benedict Nguyễn, Hot Girls With Balls" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls--199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls--40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls--33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Benedict-Nguyen-Hot-Girls-With-Balls-.jpeg 662w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Benedict Nguyễn, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781646222476" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Hot Girls With Balls</em></a><br />
Catapult, July 1<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>I’m always a sucker for a good gonzo satire and this one sounds truly delightful: two trans volleyball players, off-court romance and on-court rivalry, interrogations of celebrity and sports and gender… It looks funny as hell and willing to burn it all down, which we frankly need more of in our literature. <em>–Drew Broussard, Podcasts Editor, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255691" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/91pb-0lepfl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Loretta Rothschild, Finding Grace" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255691" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" alt="Loretta Rothschild, Finding Grace" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91pb-0LEPFL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 658w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Loretta Rothschild, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250381828" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Finding Grace</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>St. Martin&#8217;s, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>The debut novel of Loretta Rothschild revolves around motherhood, identity, and fate. Honor and her husband Tom have a daughter, Chloe, and are trying for another via surrogate: Honor is obsessed with having another child, though Tom is less enthused. One night, they fight, they say terrible things, and then, in a truly shocking twist, Honor and Chloe both end up dead from a horrible accident. Tom is left in grief, with a pregnant surrogate, and very soon he has a baby boy named Henry who he raises alone. In the next twist, a woman named Grace reaches out: she was the egg donor, who shares an uncanny, eerie resemblance to Honor. Tom becomes attached, obsessed, centering his life around this woman who’s tied up in his life in complicated and unsettling ways. It’s a novel that will keep you guessing, both lulled by the realist voice, and shocked by the events that unfold: a fresh and creative novel about duplicity and love by a startling new talent.  <em>–Julia Hass, Book Marks Assistant Editor</em></p>
<h4><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255692" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/220239023/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023.jpg" data-orig-size="987,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Hattie Williams, Bitter Sweet" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-674x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255692" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-197x300.jpg" alt="Hattie Williams, Bitter Sweet" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-674x1024.jpg 674w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-768x1167.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220239023.jpg 987w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></h4>
<h4><strong>Hattie Williams, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593874202" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Bitter Sweet</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Ballantine, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>I love a workplace novel, especially when it’s about someone losing touch with reality. Williams’ debut explores power, desire, and fear, following an assistant in her early twenties who is caught up in an affair with an older writer she’s long idolized. Obsession and vulnerability can be overwhelming and dark, and even more so when it&#8217;s between fans and artists. Don’t meet your heroes, and <em>especially</em> don’t hook up with them at work. <em>–James Folta, Staff Writer</em></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255693" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81sakbh949l-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Giulia Caminito, The Lake&#8217;s Water is Never Sweet" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255693" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Giulia Caminito, The Lake's Water is Never Sweet" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81SAkbh949L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Giulia Caminito, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781954118669" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Lake&#8217;s Water is Never Sweet</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Spiegel &amp; Grau, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>Girlhood, coming of age, fraught female friendships, lakeside towns… say less. Giulia Caminito’s English-language debut follows a young woman, Gaia, whose family moves from a poor suburb of Rome to a beautiful town by a lake in an attempt to escape their poverty. Gaia’s family is falling apart, her parents and siblings all struggling in their own private ways. Gaia builds a tenuous friendship with two local girls and tries to fit into her new life, but she begins to believe she might always be an outsider. And then something terrible happens to her friends, and her fragile new life falls apart. A complex, precise portrait of the loneliness of girlhood, <em>The Lake’s Water is Never Sweet</em> is exactly the kind of book I’m looking for this year. <em>–MC</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255694" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9780385549615-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="618,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Aymann Ismael, Becoming Baba" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy-185x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255694" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy-185x300.jpg" alt="Aymann Ismael, Becoming Baba" width="185" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy-185x300.jpg 185w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy-37x60.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy-31x50.jpg 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385549615-copy.jpg 618w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 185px) 100vw, 185px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Aymann Ismael, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385549615" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Becoming Baba</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Doubleday, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>Longtime <em>Slate</em> staff writer Aymann Ismael’s coming-of-age memoir is a funny and deeply moving account of growing up in a Muslim family in the shadow of 9/11. Ismael writes with candor and insight about his young life, and about becoming a father himself. A book about faith, discovery, and reckoning with the things we inherit and those we pass to our children, this is a stunning, vulnerable, and absorbing read.  <em>–JG</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255695" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9781685892111/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111.jpg" data-orig-size="300,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Chloe Michelle Howarth, Sunburn" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255695" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111-200x300.jpg" alt="Chloe Michelle Howarth, Sunburn" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781685892111.jpg 300w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p><div class="insert-post-ads" style="clear:both;width:100%;margin:0 0 20px 0;"><span>Article continues after advertisement</span><div class="htlad-LH_PP_IC"></div></div><div class="insert-post-ads remove"><a href="https://lithub.memberful.com/join" target="_new" class="remove-ads external">Remove Ads</a></div>
<h4><strong>Chloe Michelle Howarth, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781685892111" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Sunburn</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Melville House, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>I’m so happy this book is finally getting a wide release. My<a href="https://www.charliesqueerbooks.com/" class="external" target="_blank"> bookseller friend</a> and I are always talking about how hard it is to find this book and how he’s spent several bookseller conventions bullying publishers about its distribution. <em>Sunburn</em> is a sapphic love story set in early 90’s Ireland. The novel follows a young woman who has always felt like an outsider. Then one summer, she falls in love with a female classmate and her life becomes much bigger and much more complicated. A story of first love, queer relationships, and the pains of coming of age, <em>Sunburn</em> is a beautiful queer novel. <em>–MC</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255792" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9780811238656/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656.jpg" data-orig-size="648,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="killing stella" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255792" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656-194x300.jpg" alt="killing stella" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780811238656.jpg 648w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Marlen Haushofer, tr. Shaun Whiteside, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780811238656" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Killing Stella</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>New Directions, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>I loved this brutal little novella—as quick (80 pages!) and sharp as a kitchen knife. It&#8217;s a story about domesticity, about silence, about love, and yes, about how Stella died. For fans of Fleur Jaeggy and &#8220;(picnic, lightning)&#8221; and feeling uncomfortable in someone else&#8217;s skin. <em>–Emily Temple, Managing Editor</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255696" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81ckjhihhtl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Helen Schulman, Fools for Love: Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255696" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Helen Schulman, Fools for Love: Stories" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81ckJHiHhTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Helen Schulman, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593536254" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Fools for Love: Stories</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Knopf, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>Schulman’s most recent novel <em>Lucky Dogs</em> had a lot of very fun Hollywood satire, and I’m looking forward to more of her humor in this new collection. These new stories inventively explore relationships at odd moments: a single mother falls for a rabbi as they tear apart a bookstore, a widow finds her dead husband’s sex diaries, and a playwright doubts her marriage to an actor during a performance of a Sam Shepard play. Finding the funny in grounded short fiction is often about pressing on the moments of everyday strangeness until they start to warp, something Schulman is very good at. <em>–JF</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255697" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9781639733118/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118.jpg" data-orig-size="540,816" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Aysegül Savas, Long Distance: Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255697" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118-199x300.jpg" alt="Aysegül Savas, Long Distance: Stories" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781639733118.jpg 540w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Aysegül Savas, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781639733101" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Long Distance: Stories</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Bloomsbury, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>Over three previous novels, Ayşegül Savaş has developed a reputation for chronicling the banal aches inherent to contemporary life. Her fanbase includes many class acts, like Katie Kitamura, Sigrid Nunez, and just about everybody at <em>The New Yorker</em>. The thirteen stories in this debut collection make a case for her gifts at compression. Some pieces, like “<a href="https://www.theparisreview.org/fiction/7588/layover-aysegul-savas" class="external" target="_blank">Layover,</a>” have appeared in print before. But a few are fresh off the presses. With this one, I’m looking forward to luxuriating in many well-wrought, elegant sentences. Ideally as I ride a European train. <em>–Brittany Allen, Staff Writer</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255698" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9780316496544-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-scaled.jpg" data-orig-size="1645,2560" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Sam Kean, Dinner with King Tut" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-193x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-658x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255698" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-193x300.jpg" alt="Sam Kean, Dinner with King Tut" width="193" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-193x300.jpg 193w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-658x1024.jpg 658w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-768x1195.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-987x1536.jpg 987w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-1316x2048.jpg 1316w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780316496544-copy-scaled.jpg 1645w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 193px) 100vw, 193px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Sam Kean, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316496551" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Dinner with King Tut</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Little, Brown, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>Apparently there’s a “rogue” collection of archaeologists who’ve dedicated their lives to recreating living history, going beyond visual evocations of the past by recreating the sounds and smells and <i>feelings</i> of ancient civilizations. In <i>Dinner with King Tut</i> writer Sam Kean travels the world alongside these experiential historians as they cook Roman meals, fire Medieval cannons, and even make their own human mummies. (This is how history should be taught, no?) <em>–JD</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255699" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9780385551076-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="636,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Charlotte Runcie, Bring the House Down" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy-191x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255699" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy-191x300.jpg" alt="Charlotte Runcie, Bring the House Down" width="191" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy-191x300.jpg 191w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy-38x60.jpg 38w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780385551076-copy.jpg 636w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 191px) 100vw, 191px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Charlotte Runcie, <a class="external" href="http://bookshop.org/a/132/9780385551076" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Bring the House Down</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Doubleday, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>I’m still a theater kid at heart (no matter how much time continues to pass without auditioning) and there’s nothing like a summer festival—and of all the summer festivals, the Edinburgh Fringe is probably the wildest and most magical. Runcie (a journalist who covered the Fringe for years) gets theater right in this excellent debut novel. It follows a female critic who watches her male colleague suddenly become the focus of an excoriating one-woman-show after he gave it a bad review. It’s a brilliant look at the utter madness that is the Fringe, a deep consideration of criticism and art (and parenthood as a professional), and a fiery reminder that we still have so far to go when it comes to men behaving poorly and getting away with it. Like the title says, it’s time to bring the house down. <em>–DB, <a href="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our summer reading list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255700" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81iwl9ww0dl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Sophie Elmhirst, A Marriage at Sea" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255700" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="Sophie Elmhirst, A Marriage at Sea" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IwL9wW0DL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 662w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Sophie Elmhirst, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593854280" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>A Marriage at Sea</em></a><br />
Riverhead, July 8<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>If the <em>Titan </em>explosion and the Suez Canal obstruction by the <em>Ever Given</em> have taught us anything, it’s that people love seafaring drama. <em>A Marriage at Sea </em>is the true story of a married couple who leave everything behind to sail around the world and succeed for nearly a year before their boat sinks. The couple is then stranded together on a rubber raft. Rescue is improbable. This goes on for <em>months</em>. Months! Nautical drama, martial tensions—have you clicked away to pre-order the book already? <em>–Calvin Kasulke, Associate Publisher, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="247672" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith.jpeg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="gary shteyngart vera or faith" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith-199x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith.jpeg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-247672" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith-199x300.jpeg" alt="gary shteyngart vera or faith" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith-199x300.jpeg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/gary-shteyngart-vera-or-faith.jpeg 662w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Gary Shteyngart, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593595091" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Vera, or Faith</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Random House, July 8</strong></h4>
<p>Shteyngart’s new novel, his first since 2021’s <em>Our Country Friends</em>, is the story of a very volatile family in a very volatile America, filtered through the eyes of a child, who just wants to be loved (the most Shteyngartian of motivations, and the most human). “In its swirls of emotion, its humor, its pathos, and the unsparing humanity of its vision, <em>Vera, or Faith</em> is like some fabulous, hitherto-unknown creature that’s been let out of its bottle and set free,” remarks Michael Cunningham. Sounds about right. <em>–ET, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255701" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/71bni7s81il-_ac_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kyung-Ran Jo, Blowfish" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255701" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg" alt="Kyung-Ran Jo, Blowfish" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71bnI7s81IL._AC_UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 667w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Kyung-Ran Jo, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781662601781" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Blowfish</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Astra House, July 15</strong></h4>
<p>When I see a novel described as “atmospheric” and “melancholic” I’m immediately foaming at the mouth to read it (which could mean nothing, etc). Jo’s novel is about a woman who decides to kill herself by preparing and eating a deadly blowfish. If you’re unwell in the same ways I am, I know you’re already going “ooo okay!” and preordering this book. If you aren’t having that reaction, we have nothing in common. I can’t wait to get my hands on this strange, dark, lovely novel. <em>–MC</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255702" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/the-payback-9781668075531_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2146" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Kashana Cauley, The Payback" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-668x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255702" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-196x300.jpg" alt="Kashana Cauley, The Payback" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-668x1024.jpg 668w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-768x1177.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-1002x1536.jpg 1002w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-1336x2048.jpg 1336w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-payback-9781668075531_hr.jpg 1400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Kashana Cauley, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668075531" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>The Payback</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Atria, July 15</strong></h4>
<p>Summer is heist season. Hear me out. At least on the Eastern Seaboard, everyone–excepting the rich–is dangerously hot and filled with gripes. Desperation creates powder-keg situations for working class heroes. Think <em>Do The Right Thing</em>, or <em>Dog Day Afternoon</em>.</p>
<p>Kashana Cauley’s <em>The Payback,</em> which comes out this August, unfolds against that heist-y weather. The speculative novel follows the down-on-her-luck Jada Williams, an under-employed Glendale mallrat who was recently fired from a more glamorous post in the film industry. Working the floor at Phoenix, a fast-fashion house after the Gap, Jada struggles to make ends meet. Especially when the not-at-all-hyperbolic Debt Police start calling. Her subsequent revenge looks as fun and swift as the most righteous robbery. <em>–BA</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255703" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81iefl81j5l-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="659,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Laura Poppick, Strata: Stories from Deep Time" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255703" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" alt="Laura Poppick, Strata: Stories from Deep Time" width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81IEfL81j5L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 659w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Laura Poppick, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781324021605" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Strata: Stories from Deep Time</em> </a></strong><br />
<strong>Norton, July 15</strong></h4>
<p>The history of the geological earth is there for all of us to read; it can be found in the layers upon layers of compacted evidence created by eons of change—aka, strata—that reveal so many of our planet’s tumultuous changes. From asteroid impacts to ice ages, oxygen booms to planetary plant takeovers, science journalist Laura Poppick goes in search of these geological archives, alongside the scientists who understand them best. <em>–JD</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255704" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr.jpg" data-orig-size="1399,2114" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Joseph Lee, Nothing More of This Land" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-678x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255704" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-199x300.jpg" alt="Joseph Lee, Nothing More of This Land" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-768x1161.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-1016x1536.jpg 1016w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-1355x2048.jpg 1355w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/nothing-more-of-this-land-9781668087251_hr.jpg 1399w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Joseph Lee, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668087251" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Nothing More of This Land</em></a></strong><br />
<strong> Atria, July 15</strong></h4>
<p>In this historiography-cum-memoir Joseph Lee recounts the displacement of his people, the Aquinnah Wampanoag, from their traditional home of Martha’s Vineyard, and how difficult it can be for indigenous communities to maintain unity—and continuity—in the face of 21st-century pressures. But as Lee illustrates, there is a new generation of Native activists prepared to fight the good fight. <em>–JD</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255705" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/the_stone_door/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door.jpg" data-orig-size="1536,2475" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Leonora Carrington, The Stone Door" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-186x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-636x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255705" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-186x300.jpg" alt="Leonora Carrington, The Stone Door" width="186" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-186x300.jpg 186w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-636x1024.jpg 636w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-768x1238.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-37x60.jpg 37w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-953x1536.jpg 953w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-1271x2048.jpg 1271w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door-31x50.jpg 31w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/The_Stone_Door.jpg 1536w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 186px) 100vw, 186px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Leonora Carrington, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781681378947" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Stone Door</em></a><br />
NYRB, July 15</strong></h4>
<p><em>The Stone Door</em> opens in a forest, on a house composed of competing styles, “as if the architect had wrought a terrible revenge on his school days.” It’s a fitting opening image for a book that is also a pastiche of styles, strange and tough to characterize with the epic sweep of myth, the significance of parable, and the magical logic of a fairy tale. As a child, Carrington was raised on fairy tales in an English manor house and as an adult was caught, tragically at times, in the upheaval of WWII Europe and in the constant company of Surrealists. All of these influences swirl in the book, and for such a short novel, <em>The Stone Door</em> morphs a lot. It’s impossible to anticipate where Carrington will go: the adventure can be grounded, as in the smaller, domestic scenes, or more grand, like when the main character must negotiate with a giant who wants to skin him. <em>The Stone Door</em> is a fascinating and unsettled book, that always seems to be teetering on the edge of something dark, something mad: “Hardly daring to touch what I want to say, yet knowing that if I had enough space around me it would be a piercing shriek.” –<em>JF, <a href="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our summer reading list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255706" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/71q3sjays2l-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="658,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Hannah Pittard, If You Love It, Let It Kill You" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255706" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg" alt="Hannah Pittard, If You Love It, Let It Kill You" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_-197x300.jpg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Q3sjAys2L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 658w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Hannah Pittard,<em> <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250910271" target="_blank" rel="noopener">If You Love It, Let It Kill You</a><br />
</em>Henry Holt, July 15<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>Did you read the dishy NY Mag story about <a class="external" href="https://www.vulture.com/article/hannah-pittard-andrew-ewell-writers-marriage-cheating-books-memoirs.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">those four writers whose relationships all exploded</a>? Of course you did. You’ve maybe even read Hannah Pittard’s viral essay in the <em>Sewanee Review</em>, the one that turned into her memoir-of-sorts, <em>We Are Too Many</em>. Now, she turns a fictional eye towards the aftermath of all of that, following a Hana P in Lexington KY going through a mid-life crisis after finding out her ex is publishing a novel with a none-too-flattering version of her in it. I can’t wait. <em>–DB, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255707" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2113" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Ben Brooks, The Greatest Possible Good" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-678x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255707" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-199x300.jpg" alt="Ben Brooks, The Greatest Possible Good" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-678x1024.jpg 678w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-768x1159.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-1018x1536.jpg 1018w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-1357x2048.jpg 1357w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/the-greatest-possible-good-9781668089460_hr.jpg 1400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Ben Brooks, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668089460" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Greatest Possible Good</em></a><br />
Avid Reader Press, July 15<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>You’ll not forget the Candlewicks once you meet them! This splendid, wry satire is about a wealthy family, self-important and confident in their morality, whose blithe and bumptious existences are thrown into disarray when their father clandestinely decides to give all their money to charity, and so (in their opinions) completely destroys their lives. Droll and all-too-real. <em>–Olivia Rutigliano, Editor, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255708" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/818ci7rnjnl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="661,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mariel Franklin, Bonding" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255708" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg" alt="Mariel Franklin, Bonding" width="198" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_-198x300.jpg 198w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/818CI7RNjNL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 661w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 198px) 100vw, 198px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Mariel Franklin, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780374619602" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Bonding</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>FSG, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>This debut novel was feted on its English release last summer, and I’m so jazzed for its hop across the pond. Closely following the Millennial Mary over a year of career and courting chess moves, the story builds to an ice-cold, laser-focused critique of two industries structuring modern love: Big Pharma and Big Tech. People have compared Franklin’s coolly satirical eye to Houllebecq&#8217;s, but I actually thought of Gatsby in this classically structured cautionary tale about a decadent age. I’m betting this one will be the big cool girl beach read of the summer. <em>–BA</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255709" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/9780593242766/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Sam Bloch, Shade: The Promise of a Forgotten Natural Resource" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255709" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766-200x300.jpg" alt="Sam Bloch, Shade: The Promise of a Forgotten Natural Resource" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9780593242766.jpg 667w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Sam Bloch, <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593242766" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="external"><em>Shade: The Promise of a Forgotten Natural Resource</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Random House, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>One of the blurbs for this hybrid work of science, history, urban design, and social justice describes the book as, “my favorite kind of book: a history of something seemingly niche that secretly explains the entire world.” I, too, love these kinds of books, and as an Irishman whose natural enemy is the sun, I’m particularly intrigued by the premise. On our rapidly warming planet, as we suffer through yet another dangerous heatwave, a book that explores the history and necessity of this staple of human existence sounds like essential reading. <em>–Dan Sheehan, Book Marks Editor in Chief</em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255710" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/220687903/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903.jpg" data-orig-size="1000,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Michael Clune, Pan" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255710" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-200x300.jpg" alt="Michael Clune, Pan" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220687903.jpg 1000w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Michael Clune, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593834428" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Pan</em></a></strong><br />
<strong>Penguin Press, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>Though he works in many modes, Clune is best known for his 2013 cult memoir about heroin addiction, White Out, which was recently reissued by McNally Editions. In his first novel, he investigates panic, which when it manifests in the life of a teenage boy, takes on psychedelic, and then cosmic, and then, perhaps, divine proportions. The book explodes the central dilemma of the panic attack—what is real? and then, whether real or illusory, on what plane can I approach?—and wraps it all up in a moving coming-of-age story. <em>–ET, <a href="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our summer reading list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255711" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/81zzcor2ttl-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="714,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Tehila Hakimi, tr. Joanna Chen, Hunting in America" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_-214x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255711" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_-214x300.jpg" alt="Tehila Hakimi, tr. Joanna Chen, Hunting in America" width="214" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_-214x300.jpg 214w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_-43x60.jpg 43w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_-36x50.jpg 36w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/81zzCOr2TTL._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 714w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 214px) 100vw, 214px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Tehila Hakimi, tr. Joanna Chen, <em><a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780143138662" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Hunting in America</a><br />
</em></strong><strong>Viking, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>Tehila Hakimi’s award-winning <em>Hunting in America</em> is available in English for the first time: an enigmatic puzzle of a novel with a wry, mesmerizing voice, it goes down easy in a one-sitting read. Not to say that it’s gentle, or comfortable. It’s sly, and eerie, and keeps you guessing, and on edge, but in a way where you can’t stop turning the pages. It centers around a woman who relocates from Israel to America for her corporate job, and while reckoning with her new country, her new office, her new mundanities, develops a fixation on hunting. Stalking prey, feeling stalked herself, feeling the weight of a country and its expectations, it evokes Samantha Schweblin and Han Kang in its surreality and daring specificity. Pervasively unsettling, both too alien and too familiar, <em>Hunting in America</em> coolly illustrates the complicity that both Israeli and Americans have in a gun-touting culture, and the insidious ways that violence can seep into our consciousness. –<em>JH, <a href="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our summer reading list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255712" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2163" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Katie Yee, Maggie; or, A Man and a Woman Walk Into a Bar" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-194x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-663x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255712" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-194x300.jpg" alt="Katie Yee, Maggie; or, A Man and a Woman Walk Into a Bar" width="194" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-194x300.jpg 194w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-663x1024.jpg 663w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-768x1187.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-994x1536.jpg 994w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-1326x2048.jpg 1326w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr-32x50.jpg 32w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/maggie-or-a-man-and-a-woman-walk-into-a-bar-9781668084212_hr.jpg 1400w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 194px) 100vw, 194px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Katie Yee, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781668084212" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Maggie; or, A Man and a Woman Walk Into a Bar</em></a><br />
Summit Books, July 22</strong></h4>
<p>I can’t say I went into Katie Yee’s debut novel as an unbiased reader. I had the pleasure of reading Katie’s work for years when she was an editor at this very website. Still, personal relationships aside, I feel confident in recommending Maggie; Or, A Man and a Woman Walk Into a Bar to anyone who craves the embrace of a novel that perfectly weaves grief with warmth and wit. We follow the novel’s narrator as she absorbs the one-two punch of her husband’s affair (for which he apologizes, but does not ask for forgiveness—so, divorce) and a breast cancer diagnosis, while she meditates on the quotidian joys and betrayals of relationships, the strangeness of parenthood, the loss of health and of identity, how to nail storytime, and what a joke even is. Funny, sad, kind, and deeply tender, this is a book that goes down like a treat, and stays with you the way only the wisest novels can. <em>–JG, <a href="https://lithub.com/22-novels-you-need-to-read-this-summer/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our summer reading list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255713" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/9781646222452-copy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy.jpg" data-orig-size="662,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Daniel Saldaña París, tr. Christina MacSweeney, The Dance and the Fire" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255713" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy-199x300.jpg" alt="Daniel Saldaña París, tr. Christina MacSweeney, The Dance and the Fire" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781646222452-copy.jpg 662w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Daniel Saldaña París, tr. Christina MacSweeney, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781646222452" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>The Dance and the Fire</em></a><br />
Catapult, July 29<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>In Saldaña Paris’s ambitious new novel, three friends return to Cuernavaca, Mexico, a city on fire—wild fires and, soon enough, a kind of hysterical dancing compulsion overcoming the population. <em>–Dwyer Murphy, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255714" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/91tfqtuqo1l-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Stephanie Wambugu, Lonely Crowds" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255714" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="Stephanie Wambugu, Lonely Crowds" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/91tFqTuQO1L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 663w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Stephanie Wambugu, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780316581332" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Lonely Crowds</em></a><br />
Little, Brown, July 29<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>This novel follows two friends, Ruth and Maria, over the course of a twisty, decades-long relationship. The pair of outsiders initially bond over being the rare scholarship students at their chilly New England Catholic school. When they both wind up pursuing art dreams in New York, competition tests their bond.</p>
<p>This much-hyped debut from a young writer-to-watch enters one of my favorite canons (buds-in-the-city-books) and is set in one of my favorite milieus (a 90s New York art world). Call me seated. <em>–BA, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255715" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/71y5a1jmn4l-_uf10001000_ql80_/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" data-orig-size="663,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Ed Park, An Oral History of Atlantis: Stories" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255715" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg" alt="Ed Park, An Oral History of Atlantis: Stories" width="199" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_-199x300.jpg 199w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/71Y5a1JMN4L._UF10001000_QL80_.jpg 663w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 199px) 100vw, 199px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Ed Park, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780812998993" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>An Oral History of Atlantis: Stories</em></a><br />
Random House, July 29<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>The long wait between <em>Personal Days</em> and <em>Same Bed, Different Dreams</em> is a thing of the past—here comes another Ed Park joint, this time a story collection! Park was a Pulitzer finalist for <em>Same Bed</em> and he brings that same genre-bending, polyphonic style to this collection of stories about modern life and all its perfectly mundane strangeness.<em> –DB, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255716" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/220998996/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996.jpg" data-orig-size="981,1500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Rax King, Sloppy: Or: Doing It All Wrong" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-196x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-670x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255716" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-196x300.jpg" alt="Rax King, Sloppy: Or: Doing It All Wrong" width="196" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-196x300.jpg 196w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-670x1024.jpg 670w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-768x1174.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-39x60.jpg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220998996.jpg 981w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 196px) 100vw, 196px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Rax King, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593688458" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Sloppy: Or: Doing It All Wrong</em></a><br />
Vintage, July 29<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>King is an excellent essayist and critic, and her work is never boring or stale: anyone who’s read her at <em>MEL, Welcome To Hell World,</em> or in her previous collection <em>Tacky</em> knows how funny and sharp her writing is. Her new collection of personal essays takes on bad behavior by looking inward, with examinations of sobriety, waiting tables, Neopets forums, and shoplifting from Brandy Melville. King has a blogger’s punch and an essayist’s analysis—her dexterous writing is intelligent, observant, and very, very funny. <em>–JF, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
<p><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255717" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/attachment/220999545/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545.jpg" data-orig-size="342,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Mattie Lubchansky, Simplicity" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545-205x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255717" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545-205x300.jpg" alt="Mattie Lubchansky, Simplicity" width="205" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545-205x300.jpg 205w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545-41x60.jpg 41w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545-34x50.jpg 34w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/220999545.jpg 342w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 205px) 100vw, 205px" /></p>
<h4><strong>Mattie Lubchansky, <a class="external" href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593701126" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><em>Simplicity</em></a><br />
Pantheon, July 29<br />
</strong></h4>
<p>Where Mattie Lubchansky’s remarkable debut graphic novel <em>Boy’s Weekend </em>followed its trans protagonist’s attempt to navigate a bachelor party in a speculative near-future, <em>Simplicity </em>finds us a bit further into a dystopian-ish setting. Lucius Pasternak, a municipal employee of the New York City Administrative and Security Territory, is dispatched to study the people of Simplicity, an upstate utopian commune settled over a century ago, back in the 1970s.</p>
<p>While living among the residents of Simplicity, the uptight Pasternak struggles to adapt to the commune’s highly liberated attitudes towards sex and nudity; to further complicate matters, someone—or something—is hunting the people of Simplicity. Lubchansky’s sophomore graphic novel explores the limits of utopian separatism, the downsides to trying to work against an oppressive system from the inside, and how communities can defend themselves and win. <em>–CK, <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025/7/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">as recommended in our first-half of 2025 list</a></em></p>
										
										<div class="content-page-links"><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num prev-link"></span></a><span class="page-link-numbers"> <span class="post-page-numbers current" aria-current="page"><span class="page-link-num">1</span></span> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">2</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/3/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">3</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/4/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">4</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/5/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">5</span></a> <a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/6/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num">6</span></a></span> <a href="?single=true">Full Page</a><a href="https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2025-part-two/2/" class="post-page-numbers"><span class="page-link-num next-link">&gt;&gt;</span></a></div>										
																		
										<div class="post_wrapper author">
											<div id="about_the_author">
												<div class="gravatar"><a href="https://lithub.com/author/literary-hub/"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/xAlNwL1E_400x400-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/11/xAlNwL1E_400x400-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="Literary Hub" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></a></div>
												<div class="description author withsidebar">
